LEAD = """<strong>A gold off-take agreement is a long-term contract in which a buyer commits to purchase some or all of a producer's future gold output, typically at a formula price referencing the LBMA benchmark at each delivery.</strong> The producer gains revenue certainty and often financing leverage; the buyer secures reliable physical supply without owning the mine. Off-takes are the backbone of long-term supply relationships between producers, refineries and trading houses."""

BODY = """
<h2>What an Off-Take Agreement Contains</h2>
<ul>
<li><strong>Quantity and duration</strong> &mdash; a fixed schedule (e.g. 50 kg per month for 24 months) or a share of production (e.g. 100% of mine output), with tolerance ranges.</li>
<li><strong>Quality and form</strong> &mdash; <a href="/knowledge/what-is-gold-dore/">dor&eacute;</a> within defined assay ranges, or refined bars of stated fineness.</li>
<li><strong>Pricing formula</strong> &mdash; almost always floating: a percentage of the <a href="/knowledge/what-is-lbma-pricing/">LBMA Gold Price</a> fixing on or around each delivery's assay date, rather than a fixed price for the whole term.</li>
<li><strong>Delivery basis</strong> &mdash; commonly <a href="/knowledge/what-is-a-cif-gold-transaction/">CIF to the refinery</a>, with the assay and settlement mechanics defined per delivery.</li>
<li><strong>Payment security</strong> &mdash; letters of credit per shipment, and often a <a href="/knowledge/dlc-vs-sblc-explained/">standby letter of credit</a> or guarantee securing the longer-term commitment on one or both sides.</li>
<li><strong>Failure mechanics</strong> &mdash; remedies for missed deliveries or missed payments, force majeure, and termination rights.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Why Producers Sign Off-Takes</h2>
<p>Revenue certainty is the obvious benefit, but the deeper one is <strong>financeability</strong>. A bankable off-take with a credible buyer transforms a mine's future production into a contracted cash flow, which lenders and investors will finance. Off-take agreements are frequently a condition of project finance for new mines, and producers in need of working capital may grant off-takes in exchange for prepayment or advances.</p>

<h2>Why Buyers Sign Them</h2>
<p>Refineries need throughput; trading houses need reliable physical flow to supply their own customers. An off-take secures supply without the capital cost and operating risk of mine ownership. Because pricing floats with the benchmark, the buyer is not betting on the gold price &mdash; it is buying certainty of <em>volume</em>, often at a modest discount reflecting the producer's need for certainty and any financing provided.</p>

<h2>Example</h2>
<p>A mid-size producer signs a 24-month off-take with a refinery's trading arm: 40 kg of dor&eacute; per month &plusmn;10%, CIF Dubai, priced at 98.75% of the LBMA PM fixing on each lot's final assay date, less scheduled refining charges. Each delivery is paid under a sight letter of credit; the buyer additionally provides a standby covering one month's average value as security for the relationship. The producer uses the contracted revenue stream to raise working capital; the refinery locks in two years of feedstock.</p>

<h2>Off-Take vs Spot Selling</h2>
<table>
<tr><th></th><th>Off-take</th><th>Spot sales</th></tr>
<tr><td>Volume certainty</td><td>Contracted, both sides</td><td>None — each deal renegotiated</td></tr>
<tr><td>Price</td><td>Formula vs benchmark each delivery</td><td>Negotiated each sale</td></tr>
<tr><td>Financing value</td><td>High — bankable cash flow</td><td>Low</td></tr>
<tr><td>Flexibility</td><td>Low — committed output</td><td>High</td></tr>
<tr><td>Counterparty risk</td><td>Concentrated, long-term</td><td>Diversified, per-deal</td></tr>
</table>

<h2>What to Diligence Before Signing</h2>
<p>For buyers: the producer's actual production capacity and history, licence status, origin and <a href="/knowledge/responsible-gold-sourcing/">responsible sourcing</a> compliance, and realistic delivery schedules. For producers: the buyer's financial standing, the workability of the payment instruments, and the precise mechanics of pricing, assay rights and charges. An off-take is only as good as its weakest delivery cycle — the per-shipment mechanics deserve as much attention as the headline volume.</p>
"""

